[1]
Date: Thu 31 May 2012
Source: The Australian [edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/health-science/hendra-virus-fears-as-11-people-exposed/story-e6frg8y6-1226375619561


A total of 11 people at 2 Queensland properties have been exposed to the potentially fatal Hendra virus in the 1st outbreaks of the "high-risk" winter period as scientists await approval for the "emergency use" of a new horse vaccine.

Authorities yesterday [30 May 2012] conducted health assessments on the owners and treating veterinarians of 2 horses that died after contracting the deadly flying fox-borne disease in separate cases more than 800 km [500 mi] apart.

Officials also assessed other horses, cats, and dogs on the properties where the horses died -- one in the far north Queensland town of Ingham on Sunday [27 May 2012] and the other outside central Queensland's Rockhampton on Saturday [26 May 2012]. Quarantine exclusion zones were established.

Queensland chief veterinary officer Rick Symons warned that the state was entering the "high-risk" Hendra period, but said the virus could occur any time throughout the year, citing a case in Townsville in January 2012.

But he said it was unusual for 2 cases to occur at almost the same time in different regions. "They are at virtually the same time and we don't know whether that is a coincidence or an indication of things to come," he said. "Every Hendra case concerns us because it's a risk to horses and it's a risk to people."

Queensland's chief health officer, Jeannette Young, last night [30 May 2012] said public health experts had determined all 11 people exposed in the latest outbreaks had a "low level" of risk.

Hendra virus was declared endemic across Queensland and NSW last year [2011] after the worst reported outbreak, in which 22 horses died and a dog was euthanized.

It is transmitted from asymptomatic flying foxes to horses, and can then spread to humans in rare cases. 4 of the 7 confirmed human cases since 1994 have been fatal.

Small trials of a CSIRO [Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]-developed Hendra vaccine are under way. Australian Animal Health Laboratory veterinary pathologist Deborah Middleton said the agency was working with a commercial manufacturer in the hope of achieving a widespread release of the vaccine next year [2013].

The Queensland Liberal National Party government has committed to allowing communities with pest flying fox populations to move them on, amid fears of Hendra outbreaks.

But Environment Minister Andrew Powell warned that it was "not open season on bats" and said approvals were not yet established.

A horse died near Rockhampton on Saturday night [26 May 2012]. Then on Sunday, another horse, near Ingham, died.

[Byline: Rosanne Barrett]

