[2]
Date: Fri 1 Jun 2012
From: Emma Wilkins <emma.wilkins@csiro.au> [edited]


Re: Hendra virus horse vaccine research
---------------------------------------
CSIRO maintains a significant program of research on bat-borne viruses, including Hendra virus research.

To date the infection pathway of humans with Hendra virus has been from bats to horses, then from horses to humans -- there is no evidence of human-to-human transmission or of direct transmission of the virus from bats to humans. Given this scenario, CSIRO believes the best opportunity for intervention in the human infection pathway is to vaccinate horses to prevent the disease in horses and reduce virus shedding; both of these are critical to reduce the risk of spread of the virus to people.

We are currently undertaking studies to evaluate the level and duration of protection and the level and duration of virus shedding -- if any -- from vaccinated horses, with a focus now on determining for how long after vaccination horses are protected. This data will guide the frequency at which booster vaccinations should be given to keep protection at its peak.

CSIRO is now working with a commercial partner to gear up large scale production of the vaccine for wide spread use. Prior to its release for general application a registration package will need to be prepared that will include data on safety, efficacy, duration of protection, and small scale application in the field to ensure the vaccine performs with the same level of efficacy in the field as under experimental conditions.

If the vaccine should prove unsuccessful at any stage of the evaluation process (efficacy, safety, or field trial) the approach will need to be revaluated. Small scale field trials of the vaccine are currently underway, and an application to support possible use of the vaccine under permit has been made by the commercial partner and is currently under review. The current target for a fully registered vaccine, if the trials and evaluations are successful, remains 2013.

--
Emma Wilkins
Communication Advisor
Livestock Industries
Food, Health and Life Science Industries Group
CSIRO
Australia
<emma.wilkins@csiro.au>

******
[3]
Date: Fri 1 Jun 2012
Source: ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-01/csiro-continue-work-to-develop-hendra-virus-vaccine/4046934


The CSIRO is still trying to develop a Hendra virus vaccine, amid 2 simultaneous outbreaks of Hendra virus in Queensland this week. 2 horses died from the disease last weekend [26-27 May 2012] at properties near Rockhampton in central Queensland and Ingham in the state's north.

However, the CSIRO says the latest outbreaks does not mean there has been an escalation in the disease.

Professor Martin Jaggo, the director of the CSIRO Australian Animal Health Laboratory, says more research is need before scientists can says if there is a pattern to the outbreaks.

"It'll be about around the distribution of the bats, but also climate conditions, and it may well be related to the habitats they have in Queensland and it may even be what they feed on," he said.

"We really don't know what the trigger is for bats shedding virus." However, he says scientists are making excellent progress developing a vaccine.

Professor Jaggo says the horse vaccine is expected to be available early next year [2013]. He says it is working with a commercial company to meet the regulatory requirements for safety and effectiveness. "We've got to make sure the vaccine doesn't cause any harm to the horses, but at the same time, protects the horses from diseases," he said.

"We're collecting that data now to meet those regulatory requirements. If we look at how normally it goes with this sort of work, we would certainly be hoping the vaccine would be available early next year."

[Byline: Megan Hendry]

