[For people this disease is very frightening. The disease could take the life of an owner's horses, dogs, cats, and potentially even their own. It is reported in some sources that some veterinarians are now refusing to work with horses. Certainly horses can be a challenge and that is made more difficult with personal protective equipment (PPE). While the PPE may prevent the virus from affecting the veterinarian, I do not know how easy it is for the veterinarian to move around in the required PPE or if it frightens a horse or puts the vet in some danger from movement of the horse.

Certainly all affected owners are anxious for the vaccine, but it is especially good news to hear of the excellent progress. Special thanks to Emma Wilkins and Dr Martin Jaggo for reaching out personally and providing accurate information on the vaccine [item 2 above].

Queensland, Australia may be found on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at http://healthmap.org/r/1kJr. - Mod.TG]
